Churn Prediction with ML¶

Author: Aybike Dilek

Date: 12.06.2021

Project Definition

The project aims to conduct various exploratory analyses and machine learning applications. The churn prediction will be the main topic of the machine learning algorithms. The algorithms will be compared according to evaluation metrics.

About Dataset

The data set contains the various attributes of the telecom customers. It is the combination of 100 columns with 100 thousand records. The target variable is the churn column. It will be accepted as 0 represents non-churn and 1 represents churn customers. Since 100 columns are quite higher, it is not explained in this part. The details of the columns can be obtained from the Appendix.

Literature Review

During the literature review, it was seen that the same data set was used in several studies. In each of them, different pre-processing steps were applied. The different dimensionality reduction techniques were applied. For instance, one of them used feature selection instead of PCA. One of them used Lasso. In this study, PCA will be used. The nearly same classification techniques were used in all studies. The test accuracy was between 57% and 62% for all studies. Some of them used Keras models, which had the highest 69.7% testing score. It was seen that this dataset had a training issue in terms of underfitting according to the literature review.

Overview

The packages were imported. The pandas and the numpy were used for data processing such as filtering, sorting, subsetting. The matplotlib and the seaborn were used for visualization. The warnings was used for hiding warning messages. The skew was used to check the skewness hypothesis.

Preprocessing

The child_flag was derived manually. It explained that whether a child lives in a household or not. The age bins of the kids were used such as kid0_2, kid3_5, kid6_10, and others.

In [ ]:
data.kid0_2.replace(['Y', 'U',''], [1, 0 , ''], inplace=True)
data.kid3_5.replace(['Y', 'U',''], [1, 0 , ''], inplace=True)
data.kid6_10.replace(['Y','U',''], [1,  0 , ''], inplace=True)
data.kid11_15.replace(['Y', 'U',''], [1,  0 , ''], inplace=True)
data.kid16_17.replace(['Y', 'U',''], [1,  0 , ''], inplace=True)
data['child_num']=data['kid0_2']+data['kid3_5']+data['kid6_10']+data['kid11_15']+data['kid16_17']
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')
condition_one = (data["child_num"] >0)
condition_two = (data["child_num"] ==0)
conditions = [condition_one, condition_two]
choices = ["1", "0"]
data["child_flag"] = np.select(conditions, choices, default="")
data["child_flag"] = pd.to_numeric(data["child_flag"])

The used columns were dropped from the dataset to avoid overfitting.

In [ ]:
data= data.drop(['kid0_2'], axis=1)
data= data.drop(['kid3_5'], axis=1)
data= data.drop(['kid6_10'], axis=1)
data= data.drop(['kid11_15'], axis=1)
data= data.drop(['kid16_17'], axis=1)
data= data.drop(['child_num'], axis=1)

The churn customers had a higher median age of current equipment nearly in each model batch than non-churn customers. The one model issued had the highest median age of current equipment for both customers. The median age of current equipment decreased when the number of models issued increased, except ten, for both customers. From this, it can be concluded that churn customers use the models for a longer period than non-churn customers. Besides, the reason for the small fluctuations in the distribution after the number of models exceeded five may be that some people buy phones that they do not use on their own. In this case, even if the number of models appears to be 10, not all of them belong to one person.

Only the at most ten models issued were shown. It was seen that when the number of models issued passed ten, the unreliable values came up. Thus, the number of models issued was filtered out after ten.

Machine Learning Models

The supervised and unsupervised techniques were used in the study. It was seen that there was multi-linearity between some of the columns such as complete_Mean and attempt_Mean in the EDA phase. First of all, the PCA was applied to reduce multi-collinearity and avoid overfitting. Then, some of the supervised classification techniques were applied.

  1. Naive Bayes
  2. Support Vector Machine Classification
  3. Decision Tree Classification
  4. Random Forest Classification
  5. AdaBoost Classifier
  6. XGBoost Classifier

The SVM Classification was not tried for each kernel type because of the time consumption of the models. The only linear kernel was tried.

Besides, the Train set Test set split was used to develop and test the machine learning models. The GridSearch was used for parameter tuning for some of the machine learning models. Lastly, the Confusion Matrix, Accuracy Score and Classification Report were used for benchmarking the machine learning models.

PCA Application

First of all, the PCA was applied to reduce multi-collinearity and avoid overfitting.

The data_num had missing values. That is why the missing values were filled before the PCA. Since the columns had not a normal distribution, a median strategy was preferred. The missing churn observations were directly removed instead of filling.

In [ ]:
data_num=data[num_col]
data_num=data_num.dropna(subset=['churn'])
data_num=data_num.fillna(data_num.median())

As mentioned in the Descriptive Analysis part, the binary variables were detected. The PCA was applied to the continuous variables. That is why the binary variables were listed and filtered out.

from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler

data_num_2 = scaler.fit_transform(data_num_2)

The number of components was selected according to the explained variance.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
pca = PCA().fit(data_num_2)
plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
plt.xlabel('number of components')
plt.ylabel('cumulative explained variance');

It was seen that 7 components would explain nearly 90% of the variance.

In [ ]:
pca = PCA(n_components=7)
pca.fit(data_num_2)
data_num_2_pca = pca.transform(data_num_2)
print("original shape:   ", data_num_2.shape)
print("transformed shape:", data_num_2_pca.shape)

original shape:    (99478, 62)
transformed shape: (99478, 7)

Test Set & Train Set

As the filling process was done for PCA features, the added columns had some missing values. The missing values were filled with the median value.

In [ ]:
data_num_2_pca=data_num_2_pca.fillna(data_num_2_pca.median())

First, the features and target were split.

In [ ]:
data_num_2_pca_features = data_num_2_pca.drop(['churn'], axis=1)
data_num_2_pca_target = data_num_2_pca['churn']

The balancing process was done before splitting.

In [ ]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
sm = SMOTE(sampling_strategy='auto', random_state=100)
data_num_2_pca_features,data_num_2_pca_target = sm.fit_sample(data_num_2_pca_features,data_num_2_pca_target)

Then, the test and train sets were split.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
Xtrain, Xtest, ytrain, ytest = train_test_split(data_num_2_pca_features, data_num_2_pca_target,  test_size=0.35,

Conclusion & Discussion

  • The dimensionality reduction was applied and 62 features were reduced to 7 features, which included the information from raw 62 features.

  • Since the dataset has a complex feature set, the ensemble models gave the best test accuracy. The best test accuracy was 61% for this study. The XGBoost Classifier and Random Forest gave the highest test accuracy. All ensemble models gave nearly 60% test accuracy. The AdaBoostClassifier had the more stable scores in terms of recall, precision, and accuracy concept compare to other ensemble models.

  • The overall training accuracies for the models were low, the feature engineering was done but it was not enough to get a well-trained model. Besides, instead of 7 features more features, which were obtained from PCA, were tried but it did not change the training accuracy. According to the Literature Review, the max test accuracy was 62% for previous studies.

  • Nearly all models proned to be churn (1) predictions instead of non-churn predictions. This situation could cause weakness in the prediction power of non-churn (0).

In this project, the classification models were used for prediction. In further analysis, more values may be tried in Grid Search parts to obtain more accurate models. Additionally, different feature derivations can be tried to increase model training accuracy. Besides, the missing values can be filled with other methods such as forward or backward fill.
